description:
## Severity
Minor
## Dimension
security
## Location
src/plugins/manager.rs:557-571, src/plugins/manager.rs:629-672, src/plugins/manager.rs:731-769
## Violation
The install path checks `dest.exists()` then later calls `fs::create_dir_all` followed by `git_clone` or `copy_dir_recursive`. The window between the existence check and the create allows a concurrent install (or a malicious symlink swap) to repurpose dest. Quoted lines:

    let dest = plugins_dir.join(plugin_name);
    if dest.exists() {
        return Err(PluginError::InvalidManifest(format!(
            "Plugin '{}' already exists at {}",
            plugin_name,
            dest.display()
        )));
    }
    ...
    fs::create_dir_all(&plugins_dir).map_err(...)?;
    git_clone(url, &dest, git_ref)?;

A second concurrent `/plugin install foo` can pass the check before either has materialised dest; the loser's `git clone` is into the winner's tree. A symlink at .openclaudia/plugins/foo → /tmp pointed at it before the check evaluates can also cause data to land outside the jail (git clone refuses, but copy_dir_recursive on the PluginSource::Path branch does not — it writes through the symlink).
## Mandated refactor
Replace `dest.exists()` + later create with a single atomic mkdir-then-rename: clone/copy into a temp dir under .openclaudia/plugins/.tmp-<uuid>/, then atomically `fs::rename` into the final name. The rename fails if the destination already exists (or is a symlink), giving an atomic create-or-fail. Hold an advisory lock (fs2 / fcntl) on .openclaudia/plugins/ during install to serialise concurrent installs.
